  "opinion": "As a hairdresser who’s spent decades in a creative field, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s confidence—especially in areas where they feel out of place. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theoretical concept; it’s the quiet anxiety that comes when someone from a group historically underrepresented in science feels their abilities might be judged negatively because of their background. For me, it’s like watching a client hesitate to try a new hairstyle because they worry it won’t look right—they’re not sure if they belong. In STEM, this anxiety can make people avoid challenging tasks or give up early, even when they have the skills. I’ve never been in a lab or classroom, but I’ve seen how this plays out in my own world: a student who’s nervous about math might skip the problem set because they fear being called 'not smart.' Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big, impersonal policies that ignore the human side. Instead, we need small, consistent gestures—like teachers who name the stereotype and gently challenge it, or mentors who say, 'I’ve been there too.' In my garden, I plant seeds that grow slowly but steadily; in education, we need that patience. The key is to create spaces where people feel safe to fail without judgment. It’s not about fixing the system overnight but building trust, one conversation at a time. After all, if we don’t acknowledge how fear can hold people back, we’ll keep losing the next generation of thinkers.",
